The poet’s grateful acknowledgment to his Muse.

‘He on whom thou dost look with kindly eye in his natal honr, Mel- pomene, is set apart from the pursuit oi common glories. He shall not win renownasathlete or as general. But the quiet groves and streams shall be his haunts and he shall gain his lame through poesy (1-12). So through thy giltam Ι counted to-day a lyric hard and Envy’s tooth is dulled. All my fame, my inspiration, and my power to please are thine, sweet Muse (13-24).'

The publication of his three books of odes in 23 Bc. had established Horace's name as a lyric poet, and his appointment in 17 sc. to write the Carmen Sacculare had officially fixed his position.
